  We explore a model of duopolistic competition in which consumers flexibly
learn about the fit--both relative and absolute--of each competitor's product.
When information is cheap, increasing the cost of information decreases
consumer welfare; but when information is expensive, this relationship flips:
cheaper information hurts consumers. As information frictions vanish, the
limiting equilibrium is ex post efficient, in contrast to the monopoly model
studied by Ravid, Roesler, and Szentes (2022).
